    "reasoning": "The user requires three main components: an interface matching the golden testbench, the implementation of the DUT (TopModule) based on the specification (while respecting the golden testbench's structure if contradictions exist), and an improved golden testbench.\n\n**1. Interface Derivation:**\n   The `input_spec` defines: `module TopModule (input clk, input resetn, input r [2:0], output g [2:0])`. \n   However, the `golden_testbench` instantiates `TopModule top_module1 ( .clk, .resetn, .r, .g(g_dut) );`. The interface must match this. All ports are single-bit or 3-bit as specified.\n\n**2. DUT Implementation (TopModule):**\n   I must implement the FSM logic described in the `input_spec`: States A, B, C, D. Priority: R0 > R1 > R2. State transitions and output logic must be derived from the diagram/description.\n   - **States:** A, B, C, D (4 states, requiring 2 bits: 00, 01, 10, 11).\n   - **Reset:** Synchronous, active-low reset to state A.\n   - **Transitions/Outputs:**\n     - State A: Stay in A if r[0]=0, r[1]=0, r[2]=0. Go to B if r[0]=1. Go to C if r[0]=0, r[1]=1. Go to D if r[0]=0, r[1]=0, r[2]=1 (based on the diagram structure, though the diagram is sparse, the description implies a priority-based arbitration).\n     - The description states: 'device 2 will only receive a grant if it is the only device making a request when the FSM is in state A.' This implies a priority structure for State A transitions.\n     - The diagram suggests: \n         - A --r0=1--> B (R0 wins)\n         - A --r0=0, r1=1--> C (R1 wins if R0 doesn't request)\n         - A --r0=0, r1=0, r2=1--> D (R2 wins if R0, R1 don't request - interpreting the fourth transition)\n     - State B (Grant R0): Stays in B if r[0]=1. Goes to A if r[0]=0.\n     - State C (Grant R1): Stays in C if r[1]=1. Goes to A if r[1]=0.\n     - State D (Grant R2): This state is not explicitly detailed in the transitions provided for B and C, but assuming it behaves similarly to the others: Stays